{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17644086","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17644086"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:03:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:03:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18037"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18037","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18037"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10751"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73394"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10751","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10751"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18037"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58860"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7184"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25081"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25083"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25102"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73394","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73394"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThere are a number of nerves that traverse the anterior and posterior triangles of the neck.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following pairings is found in the anterior and posterior triangles respectively?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Accessory nerve, vagus nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve, accessory nerve,","Hypoglossal nerve, accessory nerve","Vagus nerve, glossopharyngeal nerve","Vagus nerve, hypoglossal nerve"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypoglossal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (CN XII) is a content of the anterior triangle of the neck, where it is involved in motor innervation to the muscles of the tongue. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eaccessory nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (CN XI) is a content of the posterior triangle of the neck, where it innervates the sternocleidomastoid and trapezius muscles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Evagus nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (CN X) is also found in the anterior triangle, but it is not a content of the posterior triangle. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eglossopharyngeal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (CN IX) is not typically associated with either triangle in terms of its course through the neck.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the anatomical landmarks and contents of the neck triangles is crucial for clinical assessment and surgical procedures in this region.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The anterior triangle of the neck contains the hypoglossal nerve (CN XII) and the vagus nerve (CN X).","The posterior triangle of the neck contains the accessory nerve (CN XI)."],"references":["Fehrenbach, M. J., \u0026 Herring, S. W. (2015). Illustrated Anatomy of the Head and Neck-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","McCausland C, Sawyer E, Eovaldi BJ, et al. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder Muscles. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534836/","Cramer, G. D., \u0026 Darby, S. A. (2013). Clinical anatomy of the spine, spinal cord, and ANS","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58860"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"ques